		<header>
			
			<h1>Concern over EC management of the dairy market</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 July 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Following the EC decision to allow sales of dairy products from intervention stocks, European farmers’ and agri-cooperatives’ lobbying group COPA-COGECA has urged the EC to ‘exercise extreme caution’ in the way it releases the quantities held in intervention onto the market, given that ‘the EU dairy market remains extremely fragile.’ This comes against the background of ongoing protests over the public policy response to the milk crisis. According to press reports, the European Milk Board takes the view that ‘the future of the milk market looks anything but rosy.’ There are particular concerns that the EC approach to milk sector issues ‘are unlikely to secure sustainable milk production in every European region.’ </p><p>Against this background, COPA-COGECA highlighted a number of areas that it wanted to see addressed in the conclusions of the high-level expert group on the future of the dairy sector, including:</p>
<ul>

<li>the retention of market management measures as a safety net in the face of ‘extreme market volatility’;</li>

<li>a strengthening of collective bargaining in the milk sector, including in regard to contractual arrangements for milk purchases;</li>

<li>the adoption of measures to promote ‘greater transparency and information for both consumers and producers, especially on prices, volume flows and distribution of profit margins’.</li>

</ul>
<p>On 15 June the recommendations of the High-Level Group on the dairy sector were posted. It was proposed:</p>
<ul>

<li>that measures should be adopted (in the form of guidelines or a legislative proposal) to enhance formal written contracts to cover deliveries of raw milk;</li>

<li>to expand the scope for milk producers to collectively bargain with milk processors;</li>

<li>to launch an examination of ‘whether any of the current provisions for inter-professional organisations in the fruit &amp; vegetable sector could also be applicable in the dairy sector’;</li>

<li>that the European Food Price Monitoring Tool should be further elaborated in order to enhance transparency in the dairy supply chain;</li>

<li>that consideration be given to ‘green-box compatible’ instruments to reduce income volatility, including possibly facilitating the use of futures markets, in particular via targeted training programmes;</li>

<li>to explore the ‘feasibility of different options for ‘place of farming’ labelling for dairy products’ and the introduction of a requirement for ‘distinct labelling for imitation dairy products’;</li>

<li>to improve communication about ‘the current possibilities for innovation and research within the existing framework of rural development and research framework programmes’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Commissioner Dacian Cioloş welcomed the report, and is studying its conclusions with a view to coming forward with legislative proposals before the end of the year.</p><p>COPA-COGECA Secretary-General Pekka Pesonen said that the report answered some of the demands put forward by COPA-COGECA, ‘especially maintenance of current measures to manage the market’. He called for early action to turn recommendations into concrete proposals ‘so that dairy farmers can be secured a future, and employment can be maintained in the rural areas of the EU.’</p><p>The European Dairy Association, while welcoming the group’s recommendations, regretted that the experts had ‘not undertaken a broader reflection on the competitiveness of the whole sector and further explored instruments to tackle new challenges, such as extreme price volatility.’ </p><p>The president of the European Milk Board (EMB), Romuald Schaber, said for his part that ‘the recommendations made to the European Commission by the high-level group on milk cannot improve either the milk producers’ situation or that of consumers in Europe,’ since it failed to address the issue of how the fairness of existing contracts could be improved, given the weak position of milk producers. He called for a new system be introduced ‘that gives the milk producers the opportunity to jointly adjust production to the demand for milk.’ EMB Vice-President Sieta van Keimpema went further, arguing that while two positive points could be identified (the strengthening of the legal basis for producer organisations and improved labelling), ‘everything else is way off the target of stable milk production at fair prices, and is unacceptable.’</p>
		
		
