				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It should be noted that EU policy is firmly moving away from supporting milk production in ‘every European region’. An underlying aim of the CAP reform process is to shift patterns of agricultural production to those areas where the greatest efficiency and productivity can be achieved, in order to enhance the underlying competitiveness of the EU dairy sector, a development which would serve to improve the position of EU dairy companies in their efforts to exploit the opportunities arising from rapidly growing global demand for value-added dairy products. Moves towards strengthening the functioning of the dairy supply chain need to be seen against the backdrop of the dual objective of averting any further crisis in the milk sector, which could fundamentally undermine the production base for milk in the EU, and equipping EU dairy exporters to be able to take advantage of expanding global markets for high-value dairy products.</p><p>The importance attached to developing new policy tools to ensure that periodic crises do not fundamentally undermine the agricultural production base is an issue of direct relevance to the ACP, given the heightened price instability expected on global markets in the coming years. </p>
		</div>
		
